{"title_page": "GameSim", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=November 2014}}\n{{more citations needed|date=June 2013}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name  = GameSim Inc\n| logo  = \n| caption       = \n| type  = Developer\n| foundation    = [[Orlando, Florida]], 2008\n| location      = 13501 Ingenuity Drive, Suite 310<br />[[Orlando, Florida]] 32826\n| key_people    = Max Acree (Studio Head)\n| industry      = \n| products      = Conform, Ruin, Engage, PMGS\n| revenue       = \n| owner         = \n| num_employees = ~40\n| parent        = \n| homepage      = http://gamesim.com/\n}}\n'''GameSim''' is an [[United States|American]] [[video game developer]] founded in 2008 by Andrew Tosh. GameSim has a history of developing on different platforms, but has primarily focused on [[Xbox 360]], [[Xbox One]], [[Sony PS3]], [[Sony PS4]], PC platforms.<ref name=\"Founded 2008\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/orlando/print-edition/2011/10/07/orlando-video-game-industry-revs-up.html|title=Orlando Video Games Industry Revs Up|author=Richard Bilbao|publisher=Orlando Business Journal|accessdate=June 2013 |date=2011-10-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, GameSim was named the 466th fastest growing company in the United States by Inc.<ref name=\"Inc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.inc.com/profile/gamesim |title=GameSim|website=Inc.com}}</ref> Additionally, GameSim was named the 890th fastest growing company in the Inc 5000 list in 2014.<ref name=\"Inc\" /> The company also received an award from GrowFL's Florida Companies to Watch list. There were over 450 applicants to GrowFL, and GameSim was honored as one of fifty companies to watch in Florida in 2014.<ref name=\"GrowFL\">{{cite web|url=http://flctw.growfl.com/ |title=GrowFL 2014 Florida Companies to Watch|website=growfl.com}}</ref>\n\nGameSim has also received industry specific awards, including being listed on MT2's Top Simulation & Training Companies from 2013\u201314.<ref name=\"MT2-2013\">{{cite web|url=http://dir.kmimediagroup.com/index.php?option=com_civicrm&task=civicrm/profile/view&Itemid=103&reset=1&id=44&gid=13 |title=MT2 Top Simulation and Training Companies 2013|website=www.kmimediagroup.com/}}</ref><ref name=\"MT2-2014\">{{cite web|url=http://issuu.com/kmi_media_group/docs/mt2_19-6_final |title=MT2 Top Simulation and Training Companies 2014|website=www.kmimediagroup.com/}}</ref>\n\nGameSim entered into a 3-year incentive agreement<ref name=\"orlandoincentive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cityoforlando.net/business-development/qualified-target-industry-program/ |title=QUALIFIED TARGET INDUSTRY PROGRAM|publisher=City of Orlando}}</ref> with [[Orange County, Florida]] in 2014, with the goal of adding 40 new high tech industry jobs to the Orlando area.<ref name=\"OBJ Incentive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/orlando/news/2014/04/08/gamesim-to-create-40-high-tech-jobs-in-orange.html|title=GameSim to Create 40 High Tech Jobs in Orange County|publisher=Orlando Business Journal}}</ref>\n\nGameSim was acquired by Keywords Studios on May 17, 2017 for $4.76 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/business/technology/os-bz-gamesim-acquisition-20170517-story.html|title=Orlando's GameSim bought by company that has worked on Uncharted, Call of Duty|last=Santana|first=Marco|work=OrlandoSentinel.com|access-date=2017-05-21|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Simulation ==\nIn 2011, [[NASA]] awarded GameSim a SBIR to develop a \"Virtual Team Training Engine and Evaluation Framework\".<ref name=\"NASA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/orlando/news/2011/12/02/florida-firms-get-nasa-grants.html|title=Florida Firms get NASA Grants|publisher=Orlando Business Journal|date=2011-12-02|accessdate=June 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, [[United States Air Force]] awarded GameSim a SBIR to develop a \"Tactical Training Rehearsal Environment (TTRE)\".<ref name=\"US Air Force\">{{cite web|url=http://gamesim.com/news/us-air-force-selects-gamesim-small-business-innovation-research-sbir-award |title=US Air Force Selects GameSim|date=2011-11-02|website=GameSim|accessdate=June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"KMI Air Force\">{{cite web|url= http://www.kmimediagroup.com/military-training-technology/440-articles-mtt/u-s-air-force-selects-gamesim-for-small-business-innovation-research-sbir-award/5396-u-s-air-force-selects-gamesim-for-small-business-innovation-research-sbir-award | title=U.S. Air Force Selects GameSim for Small Business Innovation Research (SBIR) Award}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2013, [[CSX]] released train simulator CSX Moves<ref name=\"CSX Moves\">{{cite web|url=http://www.csx.com/index.cfm/customers/customer-service/csx-moves-simulation/|title=CSX Moves Simulation|website=CSX.com}}</ref> in which GameSim provided all game design, art, and engineering work.<ref name=\"CSX Moves PR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesim.com/news/gamesim-exhibits-gametech-2013-conference|title=GameSim Exhibits GameTech at 2013 Conference|website=GameSim}}</ref>\n\n[[United States Army Research Laboratory|U.S. Army Research Laboratory]] Awarded GameSim with a procedural model generation service (PMGS) contract in April 2014. PMGS allows the static model creation process to be streamlined. New content is able to be generated by allowing users to skip the step of recreating an entire model library.<ref name=\"USARL\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesim.com/news/us-army-research-laboratory-awards-gamesim-procedural-model-generation-service-contract|title=US Army Research Laboratory Awards GameSim Procedural Model Generation Service Contract|website=GameSim}}</ref>\n\n== GIS ==\nIn January 2013, GameSim released ''Conform'' a software product for viewing, editing and analyzing Geographic Information System (GIS) data.<ref name=\"Conform\">{{cite web|url=http://www.prweb.com/releases/2013/1/prweb10367705.htm|title=GameSim|publisher=PRWeb|date=2013-01-29|accessdate=June 2013}}</ref> This can be paired with GameSim's PMGS product.<ref name=\"USARL\" />\n\n== Gaming ==\nGameSim has performed work as a co-developer for many years with [[EA]]. This includes developer work with EA partners, such as [[EA Sports]] and [[BioWare]]. Below is a list of games GameSim has performed development work on.\n\n=== Credited Developer ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Title!!Publisher!!Platform!!NA Release Date\n|-\n|[[Madden NFL]]\n|Electronic Arts\n|Xbox360/Xbox One/PS3/PS4/Android/iOS\n|2010-2018\n|-\n|[[Dragon Age: Inquisition]]\n|BioWare\n|Xbox360/Xbox One/PS3/PS4/Windows\n|2014\n|-\n|-\n|[[Leo's Fortune]]\n|Tilting Point\n|Amazon/Android\n|2014\n|-\n|[[Mass Effect 3]]\n|BioWare\n|Xbox360/PS3/PC\n|2012\n|-\n|-\n|[[NCAA Football series]]\n|Electronic Arts\n|Xbox360/PS3\n|2009-2013\n|-\n|-\n|NFL Showdown\n|Zynga\n|iOS/Android/Windows/Windows Phone <ref name=\"NFL Showdown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.windowscentral.com/nfl-showdown-lets-you-manage-your-dream-team-windows-phone-and-windows-81|title=NFL Showdown lets you manage your dream team on Windows Phone and Windows 8.1|website=WindowsCentral}}</ref>\n|2014\n|-\n|-\n|Tiger Woods\n|Zynga\n|iOS/Android\n|2015\n\n|}\n\nIn addition to game development, GameSim has performed work for EA's online game client, [[Origin (digital distribution software)]]. This work involves regular maintenance on the PC client. GameSim successfully ported all of the Windows specific logic to work with both Mac and PC, creating a single, shared code base for both platforms. This includes designing and implementing the in-game overlay of the Origin Mac client.<ref name=\"GS Origin\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesim.com/origin|title=Origin|website=GameSim}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.gamesim.com/}}\n\n[[Category:Companies established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Video game companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Video game development companies]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=November 2014}}\n{{more citations needed|date=Jun